    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>17 April 5620</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sirâ€”</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I enclose you<lb/> a copy of the letter written by
                    <persName>Mrs<lb/> Samuel Benjamin</persName> to <persName>Sir M.
                        Cod<add>?</add></persName><lb/> which accompanied the Bible<lb/> sent him.
                The vol was beautifully<lb/> bound in blue velvet &amp; gilt edges.<lb/> The clasps
                &amp; border of the covers<lb/> were of silver, as was also<lb/> the shield on which
                were engraved<lb/> the <persName>Codrington</persName> arms. The Bible<lb/> was
                enclosed in a very elegant<lb/> case of birds-eye maple lined<lb/> with satin, the
                hinges lock &amp; key<lb/> of the case were of silver</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>The binding was by <persName>Mr John Lovell</persName>
                <del>Lovel</del><lb/> of <placeName>Montreal</placeName>, the silver work<lb/> by
                    <persName>Mr Maisenholder</persName> of the<lb/> same place, indeed all was<lb/>
                the work of <placeName>Montreal</placeName> mechanics<lb/> except the sheets which
                were<lb/> your printers. The whole<lb/> is highly creditable to the<lb/> Canadian
                Daughters of <placeName>Israel</placeName><lb/> and especially so to
                    <persName>Mrs<lb/> A Benjamin</persName> who first<lb/> proposed the
                Testimonial.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I will shortly send you<lb/> a copy of my Review of
                    archaia<add>?</add><lb/> a few copies of which I have had<lb/> taken off in
                pamphlet form.</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>As I expected I perceive the<lb/> book highly spoken of by<lb/> the chief literary
                &amp; scientific<lb/> journals in <placeName>Britain</placeName> &amp;
                    <placeName>America</placeName><lb/> and a second Edition is already<lb/> called
                for. 2000 were printed<lb/> of the firstâ€”how long would<lb/> it be before our people
                would<lb/> buy up an edition of a book<lb/> particularly valuable to them.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am sorry you did<lb/> not enlarge the Occident<lb/> I do not think
                it is as<lb/> well liked in its present<lb/> formâ€”but of course you<lb/> should be
                the best to judge.</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>Having nothing of interest to<lb/> write I close; Hoping<lb/> you are well &amp;
                happy</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">I remain Yrs truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
